Data Description:¶

The actual concrete compressive strength (MPa) for a given mixture under a specific age (days) was determined from laboratory. Data is in raw form (not scaled).The data has 8 quantitative input variables, and 1 quantitative output variable, and 1030 instances (observations).

Domain:¶

Material manufacturing

Context:¶

Concrete is the most important material in civil engineering. The concrete compressive strength is a highly nonlinear function of age and ingredients. These ingredients include cement, blast furnace slag, fly ash, water, superplasticizer, coarse aggregate, and fine aggregate.

Attribute Information:¶

  • Cement : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Blast : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Fly ash : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Water : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Superplasticizer : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Coarse Aggregate : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Fine Aggregate : measured in kg in a m3 mixture
  • Age : day (1~365)
  • Concrete compressive strength measured in MPa

Learning Outcomes:¶

  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Building ML models for regression
  • Hyper parameter tuning

Objective:¶

Modeling of strength of high performance concrete using Machine Learning

  • Distribution of 'cement' feature ranges from 102 to 540, as mean is greater than median distribution looks to be slightly right skewed
  • 'slag' feature values ranges from 0 to 359, data is widely distributed. Zero here can be invalid value,needs domain knowledge to take further action. Mean is greater than median so data is right skewed and looks to have long tail
  • 'ash', feature values ranges from 0 to 200, also notice that the median value is 0, looks this have some erros(needs further analysis), from the statistical value we can see that mean is greater than median and hence the distribution is right skewed
  • 'water' , feature distribution ranges from 164 to 247, mean is less than median so distribution looks to be slightly left skewed
  • 'superplastic' feature values ranges from 0 to 32, mean and meadian are mostly same, this gives us hint that the distribution is normal and has bell shaped curve
  • 'coarseagg' values ranges from 801 to 1145, mean is greater than median and looks to be slightly right skewed
  • 'fineagg' distribution ranges from 594 to 992, mean is less than median so it looks data distribution is negative skewed

  • 'age' values ranges from 1 to 365 (days), having mean greater than median so data distribution is rightly skewed

  • Target column 'strength' value rnages from 2 to 82 , with mean slight greater than median

def evaluateModel(model,name):
    print("######Evaluate the model %s ###########"%(name))
    print("Training Accuracy score : \t %s "%(model.score(x_train,y_train)))
    print("Test Accuracy score : \t %s "%(model.score(x_test,y_test)))
In [151]:
#Lets create method to find out the feature importance 

def feature_importance_graph(model,data):
    importances = model.feature_importances_
    indices = np.argsort(importances)[::-1][:15]
    a = data.columns[:]
    features= a.drop(target,1)
    plt.figure(1)
    plt.barh(range(len(indices)), importances[indices], color='b', align='center')
    plt.yticks(range(len(indices)), features[indices])
In [152]:
#Lets create method to find out the feature importance 

def feature_importance(model):
    print(pd.DataFrame(model.feature_importances_,columns=['Imp'],index=x_train.columns))

cluster_range=range(2,8)
cluster_errors=[]

for num in cluster_range:
    clusters = KMeans(n_clusters=num,n_init=5,random_state=28)
    clusters.fit(data_df_clust)
    labels = clusters.labels_
    centroids = clusters.cluster_centers_
    cluster_errors.append(clusters.inertia_)

cluster_df=pd.DataFrame({"num_clusters":cluster_range,"cluster_errors":cluster_errors})
cluster_df[0:15]

  • Lets use model tuning technique to get some extra perfrmance on these models to build accurace score of 95%

GridSearchCV On GradientBoostingRegressor as it has given us good accuracy without any parameter tuning¶

In [192]:
#split train-test data
x_train,x_test,y_train,y_test = train_test_split(new_df[features],new_df[target],test_size=0.3,random_state=28)
  • GradientBoostingRegressor has given accuracy score of 90% without paramter tuning
Lets consider below hyper parameter for tuning the model¶
  • n_estimators > captures the number of trees that we add to the model
  • max_depth > bounds the maximum depth of the tree
  • Min sample split and min samples leaf > min_samples_split sets the minimum number of samples to split while min_samples_leaf sets the minimum number of samples to form a leaf
  • Max features The square root of features is usually a good starting point. Let's use CV to tune the parameter. The tuning suggests to use 4 features (close to the sqrt of 21).

Summary¶

  • EDA, Univariate, Multivariate analysis

    • we found out that there were no missing values and all the features were numeric
    • As part of statistical summary we observed the data range for each of the features and found out that some of the features like slag,ash has zero values. otherwise rest of the features are fine and skewed either left or right
    • as part of univariate analysis (histogram), we noticed that distribution is binomial in case of slag, ash and superplastic , and is random distribution incase of age, coarseagg,water (has 2 or more gaussians/curves)
    • we also noticed huge number of zeros in feature, slag, ash and superplastic
    • With box/violine plot we found out that cement, data is spread from 100 to 500 and density is mostly between 150 to 400. Water,superplastic,fineagg and age features has outliers.
    • As part of Multivariate analysis (pair plot) we didn't see much correlation between independent variables , also as part of pair plot analysis we saw multiple gaussians. Multivariate analysis with target variable we found only cement feature was in correlation otherwise no other features

  • Feature Engineering techniques

    • In order to understand the important features among all , we standardized the features using zscore first then proceeded with using Decision Tree and Random Forest to identify the important features
    • With Decision Tree we got around 86% test accuracy score and cement as the most important feature & ash as the least important feature. On second iteration we droped ash feature and with that test accuracy score was 85% (no much difference) and cement as most important & water as least important feature
    • Low score in Decision Tree is may be due to the large spread and apparent mix of gaussians , so decided to explore the data to find out hidden clusters
    • We applied K-means clustering and from Elbow method we found out that there could be 3 or 4 clusters
    • We considered K=3 cluster and on analyzing these clusters with every features we found out that, features like water,age,cement are good predictors of target column. also noticed that in each fo these feature, only one or two groups are good predictors otherwise are weak in predicting the target.
    • From Kmeans and DecisionTree we found out features [age,cement, fineagg,slag,water,superplastic] as more important in predicting the target column

  • Create model

    • We applied multiple models to find the best fit model in predicting the target outcome, infact we tried building the model including all the features and with only important features
    • With BaggingRegressor we found out accuracy score of 89%
    • With RandomForestRegressor we found out accuracy score of 88%
    • With GradientBoostingRegressor we found out accuracy score of 90%, better than BaggingRegressor and RandomForestRegressor

  • Tuning the Model

    • In order to tune the model we selected GradientBoostingRegressor which had given us test accuracy score of 90% and then we applied tuning techniques
    • We used GridSearchCV to find out the best hyper parameters for GradientBoostingRegressor to improve the score
    • We considered below hyper parameters
      • n_estimators > captures the number of trees that we add to the model
      • max_depth > bounds the maximum depth of the tree
      • Min sample split and min samples leaf > min_samples_split sets the minimum number of samples to split while min_samples_leaf sets the minimum number of samples to form a leaf
      • Max features The square root of features is usually a good starting point. Let's use CV to tune the parameter. The tuning suggests to use 4 features (close to the sqrt of 21).
    • With GridSearchCV we found out the best values for each of the hyper parameters as learning_rate=0.05,n_estimators=1750,max_depth=3, min_samples_split=60 ,min_samples_leaf=7,max_features=2
    • After using this hyper parameters all togather in GradientBoostingRegressor the test score has increased to 93% which is pretty good

So the best model found out to be GradientBoostingRegressor with test accuracy score of 93%¶
